<dl>	<dd><a name="comment_2173" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>anna</strong> replies:</em> what a fantastic idea!</p>
	<small>
	written 27th Apr 2005 <!-- | <a
    href="/abuse/?postid=1509&amp;commentid=2173">abusive?</a>
    --> </small>
	</dd>
	<dd><a name="comment_2544" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>Max</strong> replies:</em> Just because there is no provision on the ballot paper to write "None of the Above" doesn't mean you shouldn't write it on yourself. After all, the more voters who do that the more likely the Electoral Commission will get the message and possibly incorporate such a provision. They certainly won't bother if they don't see a groundswell of opinion for it.</p>
	<small>
	written 1st May 2005 <!-- | <a
    href="/abuse/?postid=1509&amp;commentid=2544">abusive?</a>
    --> </small>
	</dd>
	<dd><a name="comment_2558" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>Carole</strong> replies:</em> My husband and I were talking about this a couple of days ago. Is it right that in Australia, where it is the law that you have to vote, there is that very box which states..."none of the above?" Can we in Britain legally write on the ballot form this very sentence? I want to, but am afraid of any repercussions, I am a 'scaredy-cat' I know, but I have a lot to lose and not much to pay it with! Anyone else out there that wants to write none of the above? </p>
	<small>
	written 1st May 2005 <!-- | <a
    href="/abuse/?postid=1509&amp;commentid=2558">abusive?</a>
    --> </small>
	</dd>
	<dd><a name="comment_2585" ></a>
	<p><em><strong>Julie</strong> replies:</em> Not sure about Australia but in switzerland voting is mandatory and there is a NOTA option. In Britain you can legally write whatever you want on the ballot, it's secret anyway, and it's just exercising your democratic freedom of speech. I spoilt my paper for the last elections by writing that our electoral system was biased and unrepresentative.</p>
	<small>
	written 2nd May 2005 <!-- | <a
